metadata.name: The Past Ahead #207
metadata.description:
Cyanotypes once were the most advanced technology to create images. When I see one today I look at it as a beautiful relic and I can't help but put my present in perspective. In these uncertain times the technologies we use to create are threatened with sudden extinction. But I feel joy in imagining our works joining the strata of history, a fallen species, the breeding ground of creations to come.

metadata.name: Ceremony #23
metadata.description:
This series celebrates fxhash turning one. #fxhashturnsone

I‚Äôm so grateful for this place and have ho idea how to adequately articulate how much this platform has changed my life, but it has. A million thanks to the team. You are so appreciated as are the artists and collectors that have made this such a beautiful community. ü•Ç

Definitely check out ‚ÄúForever‚Äù mode by tapping ‚ÄúF‚Äù or mouse click/tap ‚Äî it will animate (you guessed it) forever and will change its layout every 365 frames, in honor of this wonderful year, and every year after. Some forever modes will ‚Äúnever forget‚Äù and others will fade as they progress. No idea if that‚Äôs a metaphor but it is a trait, that much I know.

All primary sales are donated to Code/Art, which is a charity that uses ‚Äú‚Ä¶Art to Inspire Girls in Computer Science.‚Äù Read about Code/Art here: https://www.code-art.com/

Ceremony uses public domain art (which is the original, more implicit version CC0) made exclusively by women.

See fxtext article linked from the project page for a gallery of the source material and other notes.

Ceremony is also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

F : ‚ÄúForever‚Äù mode (tap after initial render completes)
P : Pause/Play
(mouse click/tap also works to start ‚ÄúForever‚Äù mode or Pause/Play)

A : Add Grain (only works when paused in ‚ÄúForever‚Äù mode.)
G : Toggle Grain (resets the whole piece)
M : Toggle Matte (resets the whole piece)

S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density (resets the whole piece)
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

If you want to start in "Forever" mode, you can append "&forever=true" to the url in the live view.
You can also add pixel density to the url by appending ‚Äú&density=2‚Äù (or 3, 4, etc) to have it render at higher resolutions by default.

metadata.name: Ghrian #344
metadata.description:
Dutch auction (13/11/9/6/3), with price decreasing every 10 minutes after the start of the auction until 9 tez. Price will then decrease to 6 tez after 2 hours, then to 3 after 12 hours.

A selection of 33 different palettes.

The brush draw is determined by angles, shapes, randomly chosen overdraws, brush sizes and widths, among other things.

- Left arrow = draw in 2125x1375
- Right arrow = draw in 11x17 landscape mode fit to screen height
- Up arrow = draw in 1375x2125
- Down arrow = draw in 11x17 portrait mode fit to screen width
- Enter = draw in full window
- Tab = draw in 1400x1400
- Shift = draw in 1:1 aspect ratio scaled to window height with 5% border on all sides
- Alt = draw in 1:1 aspect ratio scaled to window height with 5% border on all sides (default pixel density)
- Left mouse click = save as a png

Pixel density is set to 2 for all of the options above unless noted otherwise.

Please note that the drawing can take quite a while to run, especially in the full screen modes.

See thread below for additional details:

https://twitter.com/AndwerEric/status/1492619586931413000?s=20&t=N8joIBuTNzYYjmcBex0QJQ

Features:

metadata.name: Quilt #2 #2
metadata.description:
Simulating an impressionist painting with a cubist layout. This is a long-running piece that can take up to 3 or more minutes to complete.

Press ‚Äôs‚Äô to save a screenshot.
It will only draw if the browser window has focus, otherwise, it will pause.

Method:
- A quadtree is constructed from a variable distant poisson disc sample points on a noise field
- For each square in the quadtree ...
- Pick a random color or grey based on 3d noise (x, y, and time)
- New set of poisson disc sampled points are distributed based on 3d noise (x, y, and time)
- Points are used for brief particle simulation
- Path of those points are drawn with a brushstroke
- Once all of the squares are drawn, the time value increments and it loops back for another layer 10 times

Features:
- colorful: common, use full-color palette instead of colors and grey
- thick strokes: common, use thicker brush strokes
- smooth: common, smoother noise pattern
- particle can escape: rare, particles may extend beyond their bounding square
